      <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
         <head>Biographical History</head>
         
      <p>The American Plastics History Association (APHA) was founded by George Marshall Naul and
            Keith Lauer in 1997 and operated until 2000.</p>
         <p>George Marshall Naul was a chemical engineer who worked for General Electric, Celanese,
            Owens Corning, and a number of other organizations. Naul also authored and edited a
            couple of books on automobiles, especially related to their history. </p>
         <p>Keith Lauer was a curator at the National Plastics Center and Museum in Leominster, MA.
            He also published a book on celluloid, served as Leominster's Ward 3 Counselor for 14
            years, and was the president of the Leominster Historical Society for 6 years.</p>
         <p>The two men recognized a need to document the history of the plastics industry pioneers
            and started the American Plastics History Association to collect member stories. The
            association was based off of the British Plastics Historical Society, of which both men
            were members. Though members were loyal to APHA, they could not be persuaded to submit
            their stories to the newsletter, <emph render="italic">APHA Notes</emph>, and without
            enough material to continue efforts, the association was subsequently disbanded in
            2000.</p></bioghist>
      
      <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
         <head>Scope and Contents of the Collection</head>
         <p>The <emph render="bold">American Plastics History Association Collection</emph> consists
            of newsletters and miscellaneous.</p>
         <p><emph render="bold">Newsletters</emph> contains <emph render="italic">APHA
            Notes</emph>.</p>
         <p><emph render="bold">Miscellaneous</emph> contains biographical information, membership
            lists, etc.</p>
      </scopecontent>
